<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Book Character Rules:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <br>
 <br>
 1. If you wish to be a book character you must contact a staff member and gain their consent by showing them a sample role-play. No whining if you don’t get the position.<br>
<br>
2. If you gain permission to play a book character, you must then post that character’s bio in the appropriate forum. Use the information provided in the books about your character, and you can also use some of your imagination. Just keep it realistic.<br>
<br>
3. You must stay true to that character. If you are playing Dumbledore, you cannot have him suddenly run off to join Voldemort. It’s fine to do character changes over time, but don’t change them so radically that they no longer resemble the book characters.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Original Character Rules:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1. Your character may not be related in any way to any of the book characters. They also may not have the same last name as any of the book characters. If you truly want to be related to a book character, contact the person who plays that book character. If no one does, then you may not be related to them.<br>
<br>
2. Your character cannot be an identical copy of a book character, except with a different name. For example, you can’t make a character named Barry Motter with a lightning bolt scar. If you lack the imagination to create your own unique character, then you probably don’t belong on the RPG.<br>
<br>
3. Your character cannot have the first name as any book character. This keeps things from becoming confusing. There are plenty of names out there for you to choose from that are not taken.<br>
<br>
4. Your character may not be a Professor. We are only accepting teachers that have been mentioned in the books. The only exception to this rule is if a subject is mentioned in the books, but not the name of a Professor. Defense Against The Dark Arts and Muggle Studies are an example of this. <br>
<br>
5. Your character must be realistic. A student cannot be a werewolf/Death Eater/Anamagi or anything else that a student would not normally be.<br>
<br>
6. Put some effort into your character’s bio. Be imaginative, descriptive, and unique. This is your chance to create someone in the world of Harry Potter. The more detailed you make the bio, the better base you will have to role-play them off of. However, remember that no character is perfect. Everyone has flaws. That’s what makes role-playing interesting.<br>
<br>
7. All character bios should include (but are not limited to):<br>
Name:<br>
Age:<br>
House:<br>
Year:<br>
Wand type (optional):<br>
Pet/Pet name (if any):<br>
Appearance: (be descriptive)<br>
Personality: (be descriptive)<br>
History: (be descriptive)<br>
